1
00:00:00,416 --> 00:00:01,701
Hi, I'm Lluís Estapé

2
00:00:01,556 --> 00:00:03,448
and for the Qwen Cloud

3
00:00:03,448 --> 00:00:05,656
Hackathon I built BoardRoom, which is a

4
00:00:05,656 --> 00:00:07,548
tool that reviews printed circuit board

5
00:00:07,548 --> 00:00:10,071
designs using a team of AI agents that

6
00:00:10,071 --> 00:00:12,594
actually argue with each other. So let me

7
00:00:12,594 --> 00:00:14,802
show you the problem it solves first.

8
00:00:15,755 --> 00:00:18,665
If you send a board to fabrication with a

9
00:00:18,665 --> 00:00:20,604
missing decoupling capacitor or a

10
00:00:20,604 --> 00:00:22,867
silkscreen label printed over a pad, you'll

11
00:00:22,867 --> 00:00:25,776
find out three weeks later and a few hundred

12
00:00:25,776 --> 00:00:28,362
euros later. So I pointed BoardRoom at a

13
00:00:28,362 --> 00:00:31,272
real KiCad board, the StickHub USB demo,

14
00:00:31,272 --> 00:00:34,181
and this is what it came up with. Six

15
00:00:34,181 --> 00:00:36,444
findings, which are power rails with mixed

16
00:00:36,444 --> 00:00:37,737
copper widths, silkscreen overlapping

17
00:00:37,737 --> 00:00:39,999
pads on the USB footprints, and missing fiducials.

18
00:00:42,801 --> 00:00:45,603
Every single finding has to cite a

19
00:00:45,603 --> 00:00:48,404
real tool call. This ID comes from an

20
00:00:48,404 --> 00:00:51,205
actual query against the board file. So if

21
00:00:51,205 --> 00:00:54,006
an agent makes a claim it can't back

22
00:00:54,006 --> 00:00:56,107
with evidence, the finding is rejected

23
00:00:56,107 --> 00:00:57,858
automatically before it reaches you.

24
00:00:57,858 --> 00:00:59,609
Across every benchmark run, both

25
00:00:59,609 --> 00:01:01,009
configurations, the hallucination rate

26
00:01:01,009 --> 00:01:02,060
was exactly zero.

27
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:05,674
So how does it work? The board goes

28
00:01:05,674 --> 00:01:07,905
in here, five specialists inspect it:

29
00:01:07,905 --> 00:01:09,392
power integrity, signal integrity,

30
00:01:09,392 --> 00:01:11,251
connectivity, DFM and layout, and firmware

31
00:01:11,251 --> 00:01:14,225
bring-up. Each one talks to KiCad through

32
00:01:14,225 --> 00:01:16,828
the Model Context Protocol, and each one

33
00:01:16,828 --> 00:01:19,802
can only touch the tools in its own

34
00:01:19,802 --> 00:01:22,033
lane, and that's enforced in code.

35
00:01:22,913 --> 00:01:25,149
They file findings, a Moderator

36
00:01:25,149 --> 00:01:27,757
collects them and signs off the review.

37
00:01:28,357 --> 00:01:31,089
All of it runs on Qwen models on Alibaba

38
00:01:31,089 --> 00:01:31,941
Cloud Model Studio.

39
00:01:32,331 --> 00:01:35,183
To have a better understanding of the

40
00:01:35,183 --> 00:01:38,036
output, the results are shown in an

41
00:01:38,036 --> 00:01:40,889
orbit map where every finding is linked

42
00:01:40,889 --> 00:01:43,741
to the nets and components it touches.

43
00:01:44,902 --> 00:01:47,117
Because the layout critic is a multimodal

44
00:01:47,189 --> 00:01:49,476
model, it looks at the rendered board

45
00:01:49,476 --> 00:01:52,089
and draws a box around each defect, right

46
00:01:52,089 --> 00:01:52,981
on the copper.

47
00:01:55,947 --> 00:01:58,721
I have now dropped an example of a

48
00:01:58,721 --> 00:02:01,149
debate to show you the feature between

49
00:02:01,149 --> 00:02:03,230
the AI agents. When two specialists

50
00:02:03,230 --> 00:02:05,311
disagree, a Moderator runs a bounded

51
00:02:05,311 --> 00:02:07,391
debate: two rounds, one extra measurement

52
00:02:07,391 --> 00:02:09,819
each, then rules based on the evidence,

53
00:02:09,819 --> 00:02:12,577
not on who argued harder. So it's

54
00:02:12,577 --> 00:02:14,099
full disclosure, this transcript is

55
00:02:14,099 --> 00:02:15,924
synthetic, the engine works and is

56
00:02:15,924 --> 00:02:17,750
tested. But across my whole benchmark,

57
00:02:17,750 --> 00:02:19,272
the specialists never actually disagreed.

58
00:02:19,272 --> 00:02:21,706
So I'd rather show you the mechanism than

59
00:02:21,706 --> 00:02:22,619
a fake argument.

60
00:02:23,447 --> 00:02:25,223
One last important question is to ask if

61
00:02:25,223 --> 00:02:26,999
a team of agents is actually better than

62
00:02:26,999 --> 00:02:29,743
one big one. I measured it with six boards,

63
00:02:29,743 --> 00:02:32,182
twelve planted defects, two runs each. On

64
00:02:32,182 --> 00:02:34,605
finding the defects, it's a tie. The team led

65
00:02:34,605 --> 00:02:37,296
by one defect out of twelve, which is noise, so

66
00:02:37,296 --> 00:02:39,180
I'm not going to claim otherwise. But

67
00:02:39,180 --> 00:02:41,334
looking at the cost, the team burns two

68
00:02:41,334 --> 00:02:43,218
and a half times more tokens and costs nearly

69
00:02:43,218 --> 00:02:44,833
three times less, because five small

70
00:02:44,833 --> 00:02:46,717
models doing more work are far cheaper

71
00:02:46,717 --> 00:02:48,870
than one big model doing less. So routing

72
00:02:48,870 --> 00:02:50,754
by role beats routing by model size.

73
00:02:51,023 --> 00:02:53,391
Thank you for watching and I hope you

74
00:02:53,391 --> 00:02:55,463
find my project useful. Special thanks to

75
00:02:55,463 --> 00:02:57,239
Qwen AI for creating this hackathon.
